1 Intro

In this document we justify the selection of the variables in the growth ouctomes vs BPA/BPS analysis model and their coding. We will focus on birth weight as an outcome and extend the conclusions from this report to other outcomes.

We provide a special focus on the many variables measuring tobacco consumption.

2 DAG

Here is the DAG based on litterature and the variables at our disposition in Sepages.

[INSERT DAG]

Hence the final model:

birth_weight = BPA_t1 + BPA_t3 + mom_age + smoking + education + child_sex + parity + pre_preg_bmi + occupation* + gestational_age

* occupation included for BPS only

5 Variable coding

Quick reminder: Given a set of candidate models for the data, the preferred model is the one with the minimum AIC value

AIC computed using model presented in intro without exposure

5.1 Continuous variables

5.1.1 mom_age

5.2 Categorical variables

5.2.1 mom_education

Here we compare several mom_education classifications:

mom_edu_raw

  • 1 Primaire
  • 2 College
  • 3 BEP
  • 4 CAP
  • 5 Lycee
  • 6 Bac +2
  • 7 Bac +3-4
  • 8 >=Bac +5

mom_edu

  • 1 Primaire/College
  • 2 BEP/CAP/Lycee
  • 3 Bac +2
  • 4 Bac +3-4
  • 5 Bac +5

mom_edu_length

  • 1 Primaire/College/BEP/CAP/Lycee/Bac +2
  • 2 Bac +3-4
  • 3 Bac +5

mom_edu_length2

  • 1 Primaire/College/BEP/CAP/Lycee
  • 2 Bac +2-3-4
  • 3 Bac +5

5.3 Tobacco

Because the Ns vary from one tobacco var to another, all tobacco models summarized in the following table were performed on the subset of women with all smoke data available.

6 Summary

  • mom_age best coded as continuous
  • mom_bmi best coded as continuous
  • gestational_age best coded as continuous

  • mom_edu best coded as

    • 1 Primaire/College/BEP/CAP/Lycee/Bac +2
    • 2 Bac +3-4
    • 3 Bac +5

  • parity best coded as

    • First child
    • Second child or more

  • smoke as smoked at T1 vs did not smoke at T1
